def lexical_diversity(text):
    return len(set(text)) / len(text)

For the length of the text, raw length, and number of tokens, the amounts for the text without punctuation as well as without punctuation and stopwords are smaller as expected. On the other hand, the lexical diversity increases as we take out the punctuation and the punctuation/stopwords which makes sense because these take out commonly used tokens. For example, removing stopwords takes out many commonly used words in English, so the text is more varied and has a higher lexical diversity. None of these results were surprising to me, and they simply indicate that as the number of tokens and length of text decrease, the lexical diversity increases.

def unusual_words(text):
    text_vocab = set(w.lower() for w in text if w.isalpha())
    english_vocab = set(w.lower() for w in nltk.corpus.words.words())
    unusual = text_vocab - english_vocab
    return sorted(unusual)
def unusual_words_many(text):
    text_vocab = set(w.lower() for w in text if w.isalpha())
    manywords = nltk.corpus.words.words() + list(nltk.corpus.wordnet.words())
    english_vocab = set(w.lower() for w in manywords)
    unusual = text_vocab - english_vocab
    return sorted(unusual)
def unusual_words_many_no_endings_s_ed_ing(text):
    ut1 = unusual_words(text)
    print(str(len(ut1))+" words not in words.words\n")
    ut2 = unusual_words_many(text)
    print(str(len(ut2))+" words not in words.words + wordnet.words\n")
    ut3 = set(w.lower() for w in ut2 if not w.endswith("s") and not w.endswith("ed") and not w.endswith("ing"))
    print(str(len(ut3))+" words not in words.words + wordnet.words + no -s, -ed and -ing :\n")
    print(ut3)
    # -en plurals, -er and -est still not uncommon

Looking at the most common 50 words from assignment one, I can immedietly tell that many of the most commonly used words in different texts are directly relevant to the book. For examples, character's names are in the most common words. More specifically, if I compare my text, Hamlet, to the text I analyzed in last week's assignment (text7) I notice that text7 has more modern language and more words depicting amounts such as 'million' and 'many'. The main difference is the different types of language (modern vs old English). These lists can indicate many aspects of the texts themselves such as the time period when they were written, important character names, etc.

In [450]:
# Question 18.
def top_bigrams(text):
    fdist = nltk.probability.FreqDist(nltk.bigrams(text)) 
    stopwords = nltk.corpus.stopwords.words('english') 
    top_of_list = [(x,y) for x,y in fdist.keys() if x.isalpha() and y.isalpha() and x not in stopwords and y not in stopwords]
    top_50 = FreqDist(top_of_list)
    return top_50.most_common(50)

# Question 20.
def word_freq(word,section):
    section_text=brown.words(categories=category)
    return sum(1 for word_ in section_text if word_==word)
